The paper discusses compressive sensing recovery algorithms for physically feasible signal acquisition and reconstruction scenarios such as super-resolution of images, which are commonly studied in the computer vision (cs.CV) and multimedia (cs.MM) communities. The paper also focuses on exploiting the correlation structure of the sensing matrix, which is a topic of interest in information theory (cs.IT) and signal processing (cs.SP). Finally, the paper provides empirical comparisons, which is a common practice in machine learning (cs.LG).
